1/2 Recently wrapped up an amazing 5 day Colombian bike adventure with @donkey_ote 

I got to introduce him to the local high-altitude roads around Bogotá before riding to Melgar (this is the town Caro's family's "jungle house" is and that we are fortunate enough to get to call our second home here in Colombia) which we used as our base for some beautiful (but very hot) gravel and road rides.

This country is a paradise for this sport - come down and let's rock!

Distance - 242.5 miles
Time riding - 20 hours 36 minutes
Total ft of climbing - 17,057 ft
Lowest point - 1,076 ft
Highest point - 11,040 ft

Not only did Caro and Ben’s wonderful lady, Marlene hang with us at the house in Melgar, but we got adopted by Firulaiz a.k.a. Suso a.k.a. Farruko, a street dog adopted by the people at the school next door. He’s only at school Monday-Friday, because, according to the woman that runs the school, on the weekends, he manages to escape and does whatever he wants. This apparently usually means being taken in by people in the neighborhood and making himself very much at home. Luckily for us, we got to be those people this time. Oh, and he has a girlfriend, Susi, who also escapes with him, but usually to cross the street and mess with the cows.

Check my Story Highlights for the more pics and videos if interested

6 years ago @lcarofonseca and I threw the best party we’ve ever been to. And it’s still going. 

🎉🎉🎉

I came close to hitting the 200km milestone, but still set my distance record when I rode from Bogotá to Bituima and back on Sunday (182.5 km + 2,283 m of climbing / 113.4 miles + 7,490 ft. of climbing). Stopped in Guayabal de Síquima on the way and had a nice little lunch in the main plaza. 

This is a beautiful part of the country, and one that I will most definitely keep returning to. 🚵‍♂️

Finally! The search to see the elusive and iconic oso de anteojos (Andean Bear or Spectacled Bear) is complete - and in amazing fashion. Beautiful clear day (not anywhere close to guaranteed), and a mama bear with 2 cubs casually walking along the Laguna de Chingaza? This will be one to remember for sure. 

There are only around 80 recorded individuals in a nearly 80,000 hectare area, so if you want to have any luck seeing these guardians of the paramo, @caminantesdelretorno and @sebastiandido are your people. 

#osoandino #chingazanationalpark #colombia

Having heard about el Nevado del Tolima, the giant active volcano about 150 miles from Bogotá, and having seen a few photos, it was a pleasure to not just catch a glimpse, but capture some great photos. I’m not sure how often the stars align for the visibility to be as clear as yesterday, but I know it’s an unusual occurrence. #nevadodeltolima #bogota #volcano #🏔️

Back in Bogotá after a couple of weeks with @lcarofonseca stateside to finally meet my niece, Wilder, and to see @sondrafireling and @jpgerling. Got to hang and ride with my old friend @giganticbowloricekrispies too!

After seeing my family in Seattle, I made my way to Maui, to see my parents, help out with clean-up from the massive winds that came along with the disastrous fire (their house did not burn fortunately, but the wind definitely did a number) as well as get some bike rides in. Not just any rides, but some real bucket list rides. 

First up, summiting Haleakala. This is one of five climbs in the world where you gain at least 10,000 ft (3000+m) in true elevation, and only one of three rides where you do that starting at sea level (the other two are on the Big Island, also in Hawaii). While not the steepest climb I’ve ever done, this was without a doubt the longest, at 28 miles (45km). Although I regularly end up much higher than the summit of this volcano - my starting elevation in Bogotá is 8,600 ft (2600m) - going from sea level to that height is a whole different ballgame given how much you feel the oxygen depleting as you get higher. I also decided to make the challenge even harder by starting at Ma’alaea Harbor, rather than the normal start point of Paia, which added roughly 40 miles (64km) to the whole trip. 

The experience of starting in a tropical setting followed by vast open interior spaces, eucalyptus forests, pine forests, parámo-like environments and then finally near-barren volcanic landscapes above the clouds, was one that I cannot wait to repeat. 

Special thank you to @alech.de who I met at the summit and who captured some great shots!

I was able to go on a few shorter rides around Maui, but the two big goals were climbing Haleakala and riding The Road to Hana, one of the most picturesque, and surprisingly hilly, roads in the world (total of 8300 ft / 2545m of elevation gain). Given the lack of tourists currently on the island, this was the time to do it. 

In normal times, the famous, curving “highway" full of bamboo forests, ridiculously beautiful waterfalls and viewpoints can take 3+ hours (by car!). And that’s just one way. On my nearly 90 mile (143km) roundtrip ride, I think I saw less than 70 total vehicles. 

One of the things I love most about cycling in Colombia is the ability to go through multiple microclimates almost hour by hour. Maui is very similar There’s still a lot to explore on the island, but the total number of environments I passed through just on the Haleakala and Hana rides is almost too many to count.

I really hope to do this route again, but it most definitely will not be as quiet as this one.
